library(e1071)
library(haven)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(labelled)
load("Housing.RData")
df <- data

dim(df)
## [1] 75388    23
housing <- subset(df, select = c("AGE",  "SERIAL", "MARST", "EDUC", "HHINCOME", "COSTELEC", "BEDROOMS", "OWNERSHP"))

# Group the data by SERIAL and calculate summary statistics
housing <- housing %>%
  group_by(SERIAL) %>%
  summarise(age = mean(AGE[AGE > 30], na.rm = TRUE),
            marst = factor(MARST[which.max(AGE)]),
            educ = as.integer(max(EDUC[AGE > 30], na.rm = TRUE)),
            hhincome = max(HHINCOME),
            costelec = max(ifelse(COSTELEC %in% c(9997, 9993), 0, COSTELEC)),
            bedrooms = max(BEDROOMS),
            ownership = factor(OWNERSHP[which.max(AGE)]),
            numOfPeople_hh = n()) %>%
  na.omit()
# Encoding categorical variables
housing <- housing %>%
  mutate(ownership = as.factor(ifelse(ownership == 1, "Owned", ifelse(ownership == 2, "Rented", NA_real_))),
         isSpousePresent = as.factor(ifelse(marst == 1, 1, 0)),
         isSpouseAbsent = as.factor(ifelse(marst == 2, 1, 0)),
         isDivorced = as.factor(ifelse(marst == 3, 1, 0)),
         isSingle = as.factor(ifelse(marst == 4, 1, 0)),
         isWidowed = as.factor(ifelse(marst == 5,1,0))) %>%
  na.omit()
# Remove unnecessary columns
housing <- housing[, !(names(housing) %in% c("marst"," ","SERIAL"))]

# Sample 2000 row indices with replacement
set.seed(1) 
indices <- sample(nrow(housing), 2000)

# Subset the dataset
house.df <- housing[indices, ]

# Exclude categorical variables from scaling
#num_cols <- c( "costelec")
house.df[, c(1,2,3,4,5,7)] <- scale(house.df[, c(1,2,3,4,5,7)])
# Split the dataset into training and testing datasets
set.seed(1)
index <- sample(1:nrow(house.df), nrow(house.df) * 0.7)
train.house <- house.df[index, ]
test.house <- house.df[-index, ]
house.df$bedrooms <- as.numeric(house.df$bedrooms)
house.df$hhincome <- as.numeric(house.df$hhincome)

glimpse(house.df)

#LINEAR KERNEL #Tuning

set.seed(1)

# Train the SVM model with linear kernel
svm_house_linear <- tune(svm, ownership ~ ., data = train.house, 
                   kernel = "linear", ranges = list(cost = c(0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 5, 10, 100)),
                   scale=FALSE)

w <- t(best.linear$coefs) %*% best.linear$SV
w
##             age       educ   hhincome   costelec  bedrooms numOfPeople_hh
## [1,] -0.4137216 -0.1825572 -0.3149188 -0.4221313 -0.817808      0.2540169
##      isSpousePresent0 isSpousePresent1 isSpouseAbsent1 isDivorced1  isSingle1
## [1,]        0.4687827       -0.4687827      -0.4619561  -0.1439586 -0.3998732
##      isWidowed1
## [1,] -0.4788852

From the weights, it shows that age and bedrooms are the strongest predictors for species.

# Get the absolute values of the weights
abs_w <- abs(w)

# Get the indices of the two largest values
largest_indices <- order(abs_w, decreasing = TRUE)[1:2]

# Get the two largest weights
weights <- w[largest_indices]
weights
## [1] -0.8178080 -0.4788852
# pick the x and y coefficients
bx <- weights[1] # bedrooms
by <- weights[2] # age
b0 <- best.linear$rho # equivalent to beta_0 in e1071 implementation
# plot
base = ggplot(data=train.house, mapping= aes(x = bedrooms, y = age)) 
base + geom_point(aes(color=ownership)) +
  geom_abline(slope=-bx/by, intercept=b0/by, color='black') +
  geom_abline(slope=-bx/by, intercept=(b0+1)/by, color='gray') + 
  geom_abline(slope=-bx/by, intercept=(b0-1)/by, color='gray') + 
  geom_point(data=data.frame(best.linear$SV), mapping = aes(x = bedrooms, y = age), shape=4, size=5)
